<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>  
<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERIntSimplest" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration in Its Simplest Forms  </title>

  <introduction>

    <p>
      If asked for a one sentence description of Integral Calculus,
      most people will say something like, <q>It is the opposite of
      Differential Calculus,</q> or, <q>It is Differential Calculus
      run backwards.</q>
    </p>

    <p>
      While there is some truth to it, this characterization is
      woefully inadequate.
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <figure  xml:id="FIGURE"> -->
      <!--   <caption> -->
      <!--     <url href="https://www.frankandernest.com" visual="https://www.frankandernest.com">Frank and Ernest</url> -->
      <!--   </caption> -->
      <!--   <image source="IC/FredGinger.png" width="80%"> -->
      <!--     <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
      <!--   </image> -->
      <!-- </figure> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      Integration is a deep and complex subject. In it<rsq/>s more
      advanced forms it is more like differentiationg
      backwards, blindfolded, while juggling, and riding a
      unicycle. There is a lot to keep track of.
    </p>
    <p>
      Moreover, in the simplest setting integrals and derivatives are
      inverse operations, and since we traditionally introduce
      integration immediately after differentiation the most natural
      presentation is via antidifferentiation.  But in a more advance
      setting (which we will not get to in this course) they are
      separate operations, requiring distinct formulations. If you
      plan to take your mathematics education much beyond Calculus you
      should keep in the back of your mind the fact that integration
      and differentiation, while closely related, are not always
      inverse operations
    </p>

    <p>
      But it is helpful to remember that integration began as
      <q>differentiation run backwards.</q> And even in its more
      advanced forms this is still a useful way to <q>think about</q>
      integration, just as it is useful to <q>think about</q>
      differentiation as <q>slope of the tangent line,</q> even
      though it is much more than that.
    </p>


    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEStoneArch">
      <title>  Bridge Arches, the Catenary Curve, and Integration as Summation</title>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>Without stones there is no arch.</q>
        </p>
        <attribution>
          <url href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Marco-Polo"
               visual="www.britannica.com/biography/Marco-Polo">Marco
          Polo</url>
          (1254<mdash/>1324)
        </attribution>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        In <xref ref="SUBSECTIONDomes"></xref> we mentioned that when <url
        href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Wren/"
        visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Wren/">Sir
        Christopher Wren</url>(1632<ndash/>1723) designed the dome of <url
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Paul%27s_Cathedral"
        visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Paul%27s_Cathedral">St
        Paul<rsq/>s Cathedral</url> he was advised by his friend <url
        href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hooke/"
        visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Hooke/">Robert
        Hooke</url> (1635<ndash/>1703) that for maximum stability he
        should design the dome so that every cross section through the
        center would be a catenary curve:
        <me>
          y=\frac{1}{a}\cosh(ax)=\frac{1}{2a}\left(e^{ax}+e^{-ax}\right)
        </me>
        where <m>a</m> is an appropriate constant.
        Specifically, Hooke said:
      </p> 
      
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          As hangs a flexible cable so, inverted, stand the touching
          pieces of an arch.
        </p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>
        Through trial<ndash/>and<ndash/>error over the centuries
        stonemasons had also concluded that the best shape for a stone
        bridge is an inverted catenary.
      </p>


      <figure  xml:id="FIGUREStoneArch">
        <caption>
        </caption>
        <image source="IC/DianasPool.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Utilizing calculus -->
      <!--   in our analysis of the problem, we finally determined why the -->
      <!--   most stable freestanding arch utilizes this shape.  This shape -->
      <!--   is the one which directs the weight of the chain tangentially -->
      <!--   toward the base of the arch.  It turns out that the same sort of -->
      <!--   analysis can be used to determine the <q>best</q> shape for the -->
      <!--   arch on a stone bridge. -->
      <!-- </p> -->


      <p>
        <!-- To make the most stable arch for such a bridge, we wish to direct -->
        <!-- the weight of the bridge tangentially toward the base as well. -->
        <!-- Our mathematical analysis is below.   -->
        To see why this is so consider one half of a stone arch bridge as
        represented in the schematic below.  We will draw the positive
        <m>y</m>-axis downward and focus on the forces at a generic point
        <m>P</m> with coordinates <m>(x,y)</m>. Our analysis will be very
        similar to our analysis of the suspension bridge cable in <xref
        ref="SUBSECTIONBridges"></xref>, so you might want to review that before reading further.
      </p>

      <image source="IC/StoneArch6.png" width="75%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <!-- <image source="IC/StoneArch1.png" width="70%"> -->
      <!--   <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
      <!-- </image> -->

      <p>
        The problem is to find the curve <m>y=y(x)</m> with the property
        that the 
        vertical component of the tangential force <m>T</m>, at <m>P</m>, is
        equal to the weight of the bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m>.  
        <!-- If -->
        <!-- we do this, then that means that the weight of the bridge will be -->
        <!-- directed toward the base of the bridge.  With this in mind,
        -->
        Let <m>A(x)</m> denote the cross<ndash/>sectional area of the
        bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will use the following  two facts about
        <m>A(x)</m>:
        <ol marker="(1)">
          <li>
            <p>
              The weight of bridge from <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> is
              proportional to <m>A(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>A(x)=\int\dx{A}</m>. (Do you see what <m>\dx{A}</m>
              represents in our sketch above?)
            </p>

          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        Next we denote by <m>H</m>  the
        (constant) magnitude of the horizontal force along the length of
        the bridge and by <m>w</m> be the weight density of the stone (per
        cross sectional area) so that the weight of the bridge from
        <m>0</m> to <m>x</m> is <m>wA</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        We want  the horizontal
        component of the force <m>T</m>, at <m>(x,y)</m>, to be <m>H</m> and the vertical
        component to be the weight of the bridge from <m>0</m> to
        <m>x</m>, namely, <m>wA</m>.  This leads to the following picture,



        from which we conclude that the slope of the tangent line to
        <m>y(x)</m> at <m>(x,y)</m> is equal to <m>\frac{w}{H}</m>.
      </p>
      <image source="IC/StoneArch9.png" width="75%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        And so we have the differential equation
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONArch1"> \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{w}{H}A</men>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The problem here is that we don<rsq/>t know what <m>A</m> is.
        However, we do know what <m>dA</m> is. Do you see it?
      </p>
      <p>
        We will return to that in a moment, but first 
        differentiating <xref ref="EQUATIONArch1">equation</xref>  we see that  the arch
        should satisfy the differential equation
        <men  xml:id="EQUATIONArch2">\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\dfdx{A}{x}</men>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Returning to <m>\dx{A}</m>  we form the
        infinitesimal rectangle whose base is <m>\dx{x}</m> and whose
        height is <m>y</m> as  in the sketch below.
      </p>
      <image source="IC/StoneArch8.png" width="75%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>

      <p>
        Notice that the area of that rectangle is a differential since
        it is the product of the real number <m>y</m> and the
        differential <m>\dx{x}</m>. Moreover the sum of the areas of all
        such rectangles is clearly <m>A</m> so it must be that
        <me>\dx{A}=y\dx{x}</me>.  Substituting this into <xref
        ref="EQUATIONArch2">equation</xref> we find that
        <me>\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{w}{H}\dfdx{A}{x}=\frac{w}{H} y</me>.
      </p>
    </example>

    <!-- <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMStoneArch"> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Show that -->
    <!--         <me>y=Ae^{\sqrt{\frac{w}{H}}x}+Be^{-\sqrt{\frac{w}{H}}x}</me> -->
    <!--         satisfies the above differential equation for any constants <m>A,\ B</m>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!--   <task> -->
    <!--     <statement> -->
    <!--       <p> -->
    <!--         Show that if <m>y\left(0\right)=\sqrt{\frac{H}{w}}</m> and -->
    <!--         <m>{\left.\dfdx{y}{x}\right|}_{x=0}=0</m>, then -->
    <!--         <m>A=B=\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\frac{H}{w}}</m>.  Compare this to the -->
    <!--         equation of the catenary in <xref ref="PROBLEMHangingChain"></xref>. -->
    <!--       </p> -->
    <!--     </statement> -->
    <!--   </task> -->
    <!-- </exercise> -->

    <p>
      While it is interesting that the above example illustrates the
      importance of catenaries in engineering, the important thing for
      us is that since <m>\dx{A}=y\dx{x}</m> we see that
      <me>\int{y\dx{x}=\int\dx{A}=A+c}</me> which relates integrals to
      areas.  This relationship was known to both Newton and Leibniz,
      as well as some of their predecessors.  It is of such importance
      that it has come to be known by the, somewhat bombastic, name
      <term>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</term>.  We will
      explore this idea more carefully in the next section and develop
      a more precise notation to deal with the applications of
      integration.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="SECTIONThinkingAboutIntegration">
    <title>Two <q>Ways of Thinking</q> About Integration: Summation vs. Antidifferentiation</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Beginning in <xref ref="SECTIONHist-intr"></xref> we observed
        that when we think about differentiation it is helpful to view
        differentiation through either the lens of geometry (Leibniz),
        or the lens of dynamics (Newton), depending on the particular
        context.  Similarly the next section describes two different,
        but equilvalent, ways to <q>think about</q> integration. As
        before these two viewpoints are, more or less, equivalent, but
        they provide different insights. Some concepts are easier to see
        through one lens, others through the other.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum">
      <title>Integration as  Summation</title>

      <p>
        Suppose a point <m>P</m> traces out a line segment of some
        unknown length <m>x</m>.
      </p>

      <image source="IC/X0toX.png" width="35%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>

      <!-- <remark>       -->
      <!--         <p> -->
      <!--           Notice that in this setting <m>x</m> represents the -->
      <!--           <em>length</em> of the line segment which <m>P</m> has -->
      <!--           traced out, and <m>P_0</m> represents the starting position -->
      <!--           of the point, and <m>P</m> represents its current position. -->
      <!--           In particular <m>x</m> is <em>not</em> the position -->
      <!--           (coordinate) of <m>P</m> on the line. It can't be because we -->
      <!--           have not specified an origin (zero) point from which to -->
      <!--           measure position. -->
      <!--         </p> -->
      <!-- </remark> -->

      <p>
        Partition the line segment between <m>x_0</m> and
        <m>x_n</m> by selecting points <m>x_1</m>, <m>x_2</m>,
        <m>\ldots </m>, <m>x_{n-1}</m> such that
        <me>
          x_0\lt x_1 \lt x_2 \lt \cdots \lt x_{n-1} \lt x_n
          </me>.
      </p>

      <figure  xml:id="FIGUREPartitionedInterval">
        <caption>
          A partitioned interval.<!--  Notice that we use <m>x_i</m> to -->
          <!-- represent both the position of a partition point and its -->
          <!-- coordinate. -->
        </caption>
        <image source="IC/FTC1.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The partition points subdivide the interval <m>[x_0, x_n]</m>
        into subintervals.  We represent the length of the first
        subinterval of <m>x</m> with <m>\Delta x_1</m>, of the second
        with <m>\Delta x_2</m>, and so on.  In general
        <m>\Delta{x_i}</m> represents the length of the <m>i</m>th
        subinterval of <m>x</m>. Clearly the length of the line
        segment <m>[x_0, x_n]</m> is
        <md>
          <mrow>\Delta{x_1}\amp{}+\Delta{x_2}+\Delta{x_3} +\cdots  +\Delta{x_{n-1}}+\Delta{x_n}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{} =  (x_1-x_0)+(x_2-x_1)+(x_3-x_2) +\cdots + (x_{n-1}-x_{n-2})+(x_n-x_{n-1})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=x_n-x_0</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp{}=x</mrow>
          </md>.
          If the subintervals are all the same length, say
          <m>\Delta{x}</m>, then we no longer need the subscripts to
          distinguish them so we could write
          <me> \underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
          copies}}=x_n-x_0=x</me>
          
          instead.  But this is cumbersome and we are far too lazy to write
          all of that each time we want to indicate such a sum.  Leibniz proposed using 
          the letter <q>S</q> (first letter of the word <q>sum</q>) to
          simplify the summation  notation. He would have written:

          <men xml:id="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">
            \int{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
            copies}} = x_n-x_0 =x
            </men>.
      </p>


      <p> 
        <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Integral and the Integral Sign</h></idx>
        We assume, with Leibniz, that <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">equation</xref> remains true when the finite
        differences (<m>\Delta{x}</m>) are replaced with infinitesimal
        differences (<m>\dx{x}{}</m>): <men
        xml:id="EQUATIONDefInt2">\int{\dx{x} }=x_n-x_0=x</men>.
        The symbol 
        <q><m>\int </m></q> is called an 
        <term>integral sign</term>, and any expression starting with 
        <q><m>\int </m> </q> followed by a differential is called an 
        <term>integral</term>. 
      </p>
      <!-- <remark> -->
      <!-- <title>Finite vs. Infinitesimal Summation</title> -->
      <p>
        For Leibniz the distinction between the summation of infinitesimals
        and of very small but finite real numbers, was somewhat blurred. Thus
        he used <q><m>\dx{x}</m></q>  and <q><m>\Delta{x} </m></q>
        more or less interchangebly.
      </p>
      <p>
        But we will need to keep them distinct. In modern times it has become
        customary to distinguish finite and infinitesimal sums by using
        different alphabets. Since <m>\Delta </m> comes from Greek and
        <m>\int </m> comes from Latin,  we extend this convention to finite
        summation by writing <xref ref="EQUATIONFinDiffSum">equation </xref>
        as
        <me>
          \sum{}\Delta{x}=\underbrace{\Delta{x}+\Delta{x} + \cdots{}+\Delta{x}}_{\text{n
          copies}} = x_n-x_0 =x
        </me>
        because <q><m>\Sigma </m></q> is the Greek version of the Latin capital letter
        <q>S</q>. We will examine this notation more closely in <xref ref="SUBSECTIONSummationNotation"></xref>. 

      </p>
      <!-- </remark> -->


      <p>
        <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">Equation</xref> is the simplest
        possible integral. It says that if we add up the lengths of
        all of the differentials that make up the line segment from
        <m>x_0</m> to <m>x_n</m> we will get its length,
        <m>x_n-x_0=x</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <idx><h>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</h></idx>

        This is surely not surprising to you and you are probably wondering
        why we've taken the trouble to wrap such an obvious statement in
        this arcane notation. The reason is this: <xref
        ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> is a very simple form of
        <term>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</term>, or FTC.
        <!-- , which we -->
        <!-- saw in <xref ref="SECTIONStoneArch"></xref>. --> We will need to become
        very comfortable with the FTC. Later, when things get complex, it
        will be helpful to refer back to <xref
        ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref> and remind ourselves that
        integration can always be usefully thought of as adding up
        differentials.
      </p>

      <paragraphs  xml:id="PARAGRAPHCoordinatesAndVariables">
        <title>DIGRESSION:  Coordinates and  Variable Names</title>
        <p>
          <!-- You may also be wondering why we are being so punctilious about -->
          <!-- distinguishing the label of a point <m>P</m>, and its coordinate -->
          <!-- <m>x_n</m>.  -->
          In <xref ref="FIGUREPartitionedInterval"></xref> we were
          rather careless about the distinction between the label of a
          point, e.g.  <m>P</m> or <m>P_0</m>, and its coordinate,
          e.g. <m>x_1</m> or <m>x_2</m>. A natural question would be
          <q>Aren<rsq/>t they the same thing?</q>
        </p>
        <p> No, actually they aren<rsq/>t. The label of a point is the
        name we use to distinguish it from other points. The
        (horizontal) coordinate of a point is it<rsq/>s (horizontal)
        distance from the origin.  Consider the following diagram.<!--
        Suppose <m>P</m> is a point on -->
        <!-- the <m>x</m>-axis located at a distance of <m>x</m> to the right of -->
        <!-- the origin. Does <m>x</m> represent a length? If so, what is <m>x</m> -->
        <!-- the length of? -->
        </p>
        <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          The labels (names) of the two points are <m>P_0</m> and <m>P</m>. Since
          <m>x_0</m> measures the distance between zero and <m>P_0</m> it is by
          definition the coordinate of the point labeled <m>P_0</m>.  Similarly <m>x_n</m> is the coordinate of <m>P</m>.
        </p>
        <aside>
          <title>Comment</title>
          <p>
            If a vertical axis were present zero would be the second
            coordinate of both points. Do you see why?
          </p>
        </aside>

        <p>
          On the
          other hand since <m>x</m> <mdash/> the distance between <m>P_0</m> and
          <m>P</m> <mdash/> is not measured from the origin it is
          neither a coordinate nor the label of a point. 
          <!-- <p> -->
          <!-- Do you see -->
          <!-- what<rsq/>s going on here? The cooordinate <m>x</m> is indeed the length of the line segment between the origin and <m>P</m>. By definition every coordinate is the length of a line segment. But not every length  is necessarily a cooordinate. To see why consider the following sketch.  -->
          <!-- </p> -->
          <!-- <image source="IC/VarX2.png" width="60%"> -->
          <!-- <shortdescription></shortdescription> -->
          <!-- </image> -->
          <!-- <p> -->
          <!-- In this case <m>P</m> and <m>P_0</m> are the labels of the two points, -->
          <!-- whereas <m>x_n</m> and <m>x_0</m> are their coordinates, respectively. -->
          <!-- </p> -->
          It is the length of the line segment
          <m>\overline{P_0P}</m>. If we partition this line segment and
          compute <m>\int\dx{x} </m> we get 
          <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since their coordinates distinguish one point from another
          as well as their labels do, a (very) common practice is to
          dispense with the labels altogether and make the coordinates
          serve both purposes as in the diagram below.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/VarX3.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          Strictly speaking this is an abuse of our notation and it can cause
          confusion because it isn<rsq/>t always clear whether <m>x_0</m> and
          <m>x_n</m> refer to points on the line, or their distance from the
          origin (their coordinates). Always be sure it is clear to you which
          usage is intended.
        </p>

        <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
      </paragraphs>
    </subsection>

    <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsAntiDerivative">
      <title>Integration as Antidifferentiation</title>
      <p>
        All of  <xref ref="CHAPTERIntegrationTechniques"></xref> was about
        interpreting integration as antidifferentiation so most of the
        discussion in this section will simply be a formalization of
        that idea. We begin with a formal definition of the
        antiderivative.
      </p>

      <definition  xml:id="DEFINITIONAntiderivative">
        <title>Antiderivative</title>
        <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
        <idx><h>Definition</h><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose we have a function <men
            xml:id="EQUATIONDefAntideriv">y=F(t)</men> with derivative
            <m>\dfdx{y}{t}=F^\prime(t)=f(t)</m>. Then <m>F(t)</m> is
            called an <term>antiderivative</term> of
            <m>f(t)</m>. Since there are infinitely many
            antiderivatives of a given function we call <m>F(t)+C</m>,
            where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant, the <term>most
            general antidierivative</term> of <m>f(t)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        From <xref ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> , we
        see that
        
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntAsAntiDiff">\dx{y}=F^\prime(t)\dx{t}=f(t)\dx{t}</men>.

      </p>
      <p>


        We know from our work in
        <xref ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> (specifically
        <xref ref="EQUATIONDefInt2">equation</xref>) that
        
        <me>y=\int\dx{y}</me>.

        So if we sum all of the differentials on the left and right sides of <xref ref="EQUATIONIntAsAntiDiff">equation</xref>  we have

        <me>y=\int\dx{y}= \int f(t)\dx{t}</me>.
        Observe that since <m>\dx{y} </m> is a differential it follows
        that <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> is also a differential so the expression
        <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> is a valid integral.

      </p>



      <p>
        Thus it appears that if <m>\dx{y}=f(t)\dx{t} </m> is known
        then <m>y=F(t)</m> will be the antiderivative of
        <m>f(t)</m>. That is to say, integration appears to be
        <q>differentiation run backwards.</q> This seems reasonable
        since differentiation consists of subtracting (finding
        differentials) and integration consists of adding (summing
        differentials). Addition and subtraction can  both be thought of as <q>doing the the other backwards.</q>

      </p>

      <!--       <p> -->
      <!--         It follows immediately from <xref -->
      <!--         ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> and the <xref -->
      <!--         ref="THEOREMConstRule">Constant Rule</xref> that if a function has one antiderivative -->
      <!--         then it has infinitely many.  That is, if <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of -->
      <!--         <m>f(x)</m> then so is <m>F(x)+5</m>. And <m>F(x)+80</m>. In -->
      <!--         fact if <m>C</m> ia a constant then so is <m>F(x)+C</m> for -->
      <!--         every possible value of <m>C</m> -->
      <!--         because we get a (slightly) different antiderivative -->
      <!--         each time we add a constant to <m>F(x)</m>.   -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!-- Thus if -->
      <!--         we know  one antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>, -->
      <!--         then we know all (infinitely many) of the antiderivatives of -->
      <!--         <m>f(x)</m>. -->
      <!--         Remember this. We -->
      <!--         will return to it when we discuss <xref ref="THEOREMFTC"></xref> below. -->
      <!--       </p> -->

      <!-- <example xml:id="EXAMPLESimpleInt1"> -->
      <!--   <title>A Simple Integration</title> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     For example, can you find a formula for this integral: -->
      <!--     <m>\int2t\dx{t}</m>? Before reading on give it a try. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     Clearly <m>f(t)=2t</m> so from <xref -->
      <!--     ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref> we see that <m>F(t) = -->
      <!--     t^2</m> is one antiderivative, and we can capture all of the -->
      <!--     antiderivatives by adding an arbitrary constant. Thus -->
      <!--     <me>\int 2t\dx{t} = t^2 + C</me>. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Antiderivative</h><h>most general</h></idx> -->

      <!--     This shows that the expression <m>\int f(t)\dx{t} </m> -->
      <!--     represents a multifunction much like the <q> -->
      <!--     <m>\text{arc}</m></q> functions we encountered in <xref -->
      <!--     ref="CHAPTERcalc-trig"></xref>. An alternative way to think -->
      <!--     of this is to say that <m>\int f(t)\dx{t} </m> represents -->
      <!--     the set of all antiderivatives of <m>f(t)</m>, each of which -->
      <!--     differs from the others by a constant.  -->
      <!--     <!-\- However, none of the -\-> -->
      <!--     <!-\- complicated domain and range difficulties that caused so -\-> -->
      <!--     <!-\- many headaches in <xref -\-> -->
      <!--     <!-\- ref="SECTIONinverse-tan-and-cot"></xref> will be in play -\-> -->
      <!--     <!-\- here. -\-> -->
      <!--     Since the multifunctions arising from integration are -->
      <!--     relatively simple, we will dispense with the formal language -->
      <!--     and call <me>\int 2t\dx{t} = t^2+C</me> the <term>most -->
      <!--     general antiderivative</term> of <m>f(t) = 2t</m>.  -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!--   <p> -->
      <!--     There will be times when we will want to choose only one of -->
      <!--     the functions represented by <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m>. This -->
      <!--     will consist entirely of choosing the value of <m>C</m> that -->
      <!--     works for the problem in front of us so we won<rsq/>t fuss -->
      <!--     over it too much. If we write <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> without -->
      <!--     conditions it means the set of all antiderivatives of -->
      <!--     <m>f(x)</m>. To specify a particular antiderivative we will -->
      <!--     still write <m>\int f(t)\dx{t}</m> but we will also -->
      <!--     explicitly indicate which antiderivative we mean. -->
      <!--   </p> -->
      <!-- </example> -->

      <p>
        Integration theory has grown considerably beyond
        what we will be learning in this course. But the underlying
        notions of the integral as a sum and the integral as an
        antiderivative are still very helpful and we will rely on them
        rather heavily.
      </p>


      <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEAntiDerivPractice">
        

        <idx><h>Antiderivative</h></idx>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Show that  the following statements are true. Assume
            <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.

            (We have not shown you how to compute any of these
            integrals. But  you know how to differentiate. Read <xref
            ref="DEFINITIONAntiderivative"></xref>  again carefully.)
          </p>


        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int 2te^{t^2}\dx{t} = e^{t^2} +C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int te^t\dx{t} = (t-1)e^t+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(x)\cos(x)\dx{x} =\frac12\sin^2(x)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              Notice that we<rsq/>ve used <m>x</m> instead of <m>t</m> for our
              variable. Does that matter? Explain.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </task>
        <task  xml:id="PROBLEMSinsqcossqantider">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int \sin(\theta )\cos(\theta )\dx{\theta } =
              -\frac12\cos^2(\theta )+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int u\cos(u) \dx{u} = u\sin(u)+\cos(u)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int x\ln(x) \dx{x} = x(\ln{x}-1)+C</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>


      </exercise>

      <p>
        The exercises in <xref ref="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice"></xref> were all
        a bit contrived. Since we gave you the antiderivatives you don<rsq/>t
        really need to know how tho integrate.
      </p>
      <p>
        The real question here is <q>How could you find these antiderivatives
        if we hadn<rsq/>t given them to you?</q>
      </p>

      
      <problem xml:id="DRILLIntSum">
        <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
        <p>
          Entry #2 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration" ></xref>
          appears to violate entry #1, doesn<rsq/>t it?  Isn<rsq/>t it
          true that
          <me>
            \int\dx(f+g)=  \int \dx{f} +\int \dx{g} = f+C_1+g+C_2
          </me>
          where <m>C_1</m> and <m>C_2</m> are arbitrary constants, and that
          <me>
            a\int\dx{y}=a(y+c)=ay+aC </me>.
            Explain how entry #2  and entry #3 of  <xref
            ref="TABLEBasicIntegration" ></xref> are legitimate as stated.
        </p>
      </problem>
      
      <p>
        In light of <xref ref="DRILLIntSum"></xref>, it is common
        practice integrate each term of a differential and then combine
        all of the arbitrary constants into a single constant.
      </p>
      <example>
        <p>
          For example,
          consider
          
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int\left(5x^2-3\sqrt{x}+\frac{2}{1+x^2}\right)\amp{}\dx{x}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}=5\int x^2\dx{x}-3\int x^\frac12
              \dx{x}+2\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp =5\left(\frac{x^3}{3}\right) +C_1-
              \frac{3\left(x^{\frac12}\right)}{\frac32} + C_2 +
              2\inverse\tan(x)+C_3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp =\frac53x^3-2x^{\frac32}+2\inverse\tan(x)+C
            </mrow>
            </md>,
            where <m>C=C_1+C_2+C_3</m>.
        </p>
      </example>
      <p>
        As with differentiation, when you get more comfortable
        with integration, you will probably do many of these steps in your
        head.  But that ability will only come with practice.
      </p>

      <problem  xml:id="PROBLEMAntiDiffPractice">
        <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
        <p>
          Use entry #3 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>  to find the most
          general antiderivative.
          <ol cols="2" marker="(i)">
            <li>
              <m>\int t^2\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 3t-2\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 7\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \sin(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int 5\cos(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \sec(t)\tan(t)\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int t + e^t\dx{t}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\int \frac{1}{1+\theta^2}\dx{\theta{}}</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </problem>


      <p>
        Conspicuously absent from our list of rules are the integral
        form of the Product Rule, the Quotient Rule, and the Chain Rule.
        The reverse of the Quotient Rule is rather limited in its
        applicability and typically is not used.  Reversing the others
        can be quite useful but we are not quite ready to discuss them
        in depth.
      </p>

      <paragraphs>
        <title>DIGRESSION: A Few Comments on the Derivative of
        <m>f(x)=\frac1x </m> <!-- <xref ref="IntRuleOneOver">Integration Rule</xref> -->  </title>

        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration">>Table</xref> is not -->
        <!--   exhaustive. It couldn<rsq/>t possibly be since every -->
        <!--   differentiation formula gives rise to a corresponding -->
        <!--   integration formula. -->
        <!-- </p> -->
        <p>
          First,      notice that entry #4 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration">Integration Rule</xref>  will work if the
          exponent has any value
          <em>except</em> <m>n=-1</m>. If we try to apply it we<rsq/>ll get
          <me>
            \int \inverse{x}\dx{x} = \frac{x^{1-1}}{1-1} = \frac{1}{0}
          </me>
          which we know is meaningless.
        </p>
        <p>
          For this
          single exception we have to turn to entry #5 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>:
          <m>\int\frac1x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C{}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Does it seem strange to you that there would be this single exception
          to entry #4 of <xref ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref>? Us too.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          Also notice the absolute value in the formula:
          <me>
            \int\inverse x\dx{x}=\ln\abs{x}+C.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          We saw in <xref ref="DIGRESSIONAbsValSqrt" text="custom"> The Absolute Value Function</xref>  that an
          alternative definition of the absolute value function is
          <me>\abs{x}=\sqrt{x^2}</me>.
        </p>
        <exercise>
          

          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that if we differentiate the definition <m>\ln(x)
              =\sqrt{x^2}</m> we still obtain the formula
              <me>
                \dx(\ln\abs{x})=\frac1x \dx{x}
                </me>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              Be careful that you do not try to take the logarithm of a
              negative number.
            </p>
          </hint>
        </exercise>
        <p>
          It is common (though incorrect) practice to disregard the
          absolute value and  write <m>\int\inverse
          x\dx{x}=\ln(x)+C</m>, even though this is only valid for
          <m>x\gt{0}</m>.  We will also adopt this practice but you
          should always bear in mind that there are situations where
          the absolute value must be used.
        </p>
        <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
      </paragraphs>

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   If you read each of these Differentiation and Integration Rules -->
      <!--   verbally you can hear that they reverse each other. For example in -->
      <!--   line 4 we see that to differentiate <m>x</m> to a power, we -->
      <!--   <q>multiply by the exponent and then subtract one from the -->
      <!--   exponent.</q> To reverse the process notice that everything gets run -->
      <!--   backwards: We first <q>add one to the exponent, then we divide by -->
      <!--   the exponent.</q> (In the same way that when dressing you put your -->
      <!--   socks on and then your shoes and to reverse it you take off your -->
      <!--     shoes first and then your socks). -->
      <!-- </p> -->

    </subsection>

    <conclusion>

      <title>We Integrate Differentials, Not Functions</title>
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Integration can be usefully thought of as either summation or -->
      <!--   antidifferentiation. We will flip between these two mindsets as -->
      <!--   convenient in much the same way that we flipped between the -->
      <!--   dynamic (Newtonian) and geometric (Leibnizian) viewpoints in -->
      <!--   <xref ref="DiffCalcFromPractice"></xref>. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <p>
        Since it is valid to think of <m>\int
        f(x)\dx{x}</m> as representing an antiderivative of the function
        <m>f</m> it is customary to speak these symbols aloud as <q>the integral of <m>f</m>
        of <m>x</m>.</q> While this is not wrong, it is not quite right
        either. Properly speaking, we should say <q>the integral of the
        differential <m>f(x)</m> times <m>\dx{x}</m>.</q> But no one does that
        so we won<rsq/>t either.
      </p>
      <p>
        But if we (the authors or your instructor) consistently speak
        incorrectly (as we tend to do in this instance) it is easy for 
        you (the student) to develop  unfortunate habits of mind. 
        We will take a moment to try to  prevent that from happening.
      </p>
      <p>
        As we<rsq/>ve seen, the integral sign was designed (by
        Leibniz) to indicate summation, not antidifferentiation. As
        a result it is very easy to use it improperly. Sooner or
        later most people will fall into the habit of dropping the
        final <q><m>\dx{x}</m>,</q> of writing <m>\int f(x)</m>
        instead of <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m>, and  calling both
        of them the integral of the function <m>f(x)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is an unfortunate, but
        common, abuse of the notation.  You can not integrate a
        function, only a differential. We <em>strongly</em> suggest
        that you take care to avoid this bad habit for as long as
        you can because it can be very confusing. Especially when
        the concepts are new.
      </p>
      <p>
        Remember that <me>\int f(x)</me> is meaningless no matter how
        convenient it might be because it indicates that we are summing
        a function, not a differential.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Notation</title>
        <p>
          By calling <m>\int f(x)</m> meaningless we have overstated
          the situation a bit. If you study mathematics long enough
          you will encounter situations where <m>\int{f(x)}</m> is a
          perfectly reasonable notation to use. But we will not
          encounter them here, and it is best if you don<rsq/>t fall
          into this habit while you are still learning the basics.
        </p>
      </aside>


      <p>
        But the meaning of <me>\int
        f(x)\dx{x}</me> is clear. We're summing up all of the
        differentials of the form <m>f(x)\dx{x} </m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Finally, there is a puzzle here. The twin notions of an integral
        as an infinite summation, and as antidifferentiation, do not
        appear,
        <foreign>a priori</foreign>, to be related at all. How can
        they actually be two ways of thinking of the same thing?

        <!--           In <xref -->
        <!--           ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref> we introduced -->
        <!--           integration as summation, and we invented the integral sign -->
        <!--           <m>\left(\int{}\right)</m> to reflect that idea. But in this -->
        <!--           section we have reinterpreted the integral to mean -->
        <!--           antidifferentiation and the idea of <q>integral as -->
        <!--           summation</q> seems to have died a quiet death. Nowhere in -->
        <!--           <xref ref="EXAMPLESimpleInt1"></xref> does a summation -->
        <!--           appear. -->
      </p>
      <p>

        Notwithstanding that puzzle it should be clear that the two
        ideas will complement each other well. Finding the sum
        <m>\int 2x\dx{x}</m> by addition is a very daunting
        task. Where would you even begin? By reinterpreting it as an
        antidifferentiation problem we are able to find the sum,
        <m>\int 2x\dx{x}+C</m> without the bother of adding up
        (infinitely many) differentials of the form
        <m>2x\dx{x}</m>. Antidifferentiation gives us a way to
        compute the sum indirectly.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the other hand, some antiderivative can<rsq/>t be given
        in elementary terms. For example there is no elementary
        formula for the integral  
        <me>\int e^{-x^2}\dx{x}</me>, 
        but as we will see in <xref
        ref="CHAPTERApproximationIntegral"></xref> this is a very
        useful integral. Even if we can<rsq/>t write down its
        antiderivative, it will frequently be useful to approximate
        it. And we  do that by thinking of <m>\int
        e^{-x^2}\dx{x}</m> as a summation.
      </p>

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Suppose that <m>y=t^2</m> then <m>\dx{y} =2t\dx{t}</m>. Then -->
      <!--   <m>\int 2t\dx{t}</m> makes sense because the product -->
      <!--   <m>2t\dx{t}=\dx{y}</m> is a differential. But <m>\int 2t</m> -->
      <!--   is nonsense because <m>2t</m> alone is not a differential. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   In particular, <m>\int 2t</m> is meaningless. However  if <m>y=t^2</m> -->
      <!--   then what is probably meant is -->
      <!--   <men  xml:id="EQUATIONPlusCMissing">\int 2t\dx{t} = \int \dx{y}</men> which is equal to <m>y</m> since <m>\int \dx{y}</m> means  -->
      <!--   <q>add up the differentials of <m>y</m>.</q> -->
      <!-- </p> -->

      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   But remember that the title of this -->
      <!--   chapter is <q>Integration in its <em>Simplest</em> Form.</q> Running -->
      <!--   differentiation backwards is not as straightforward as it first -->
      <!--   appears to be. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
    </conclusion>


  </section>

